Ukraine on the Way to Europe
"East is East and West is West, and never the twain shall meet," Rudyard Kipling once said.
The Ukraine is undoubtedly located in the East, but in the East of Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the dominant goal for many of us.
The path there was, however, not always paved with successes, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to take this path.
I am a social democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although I was quite successful as a lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union.
There is no doubt in my mind that our "Soviet" legacy is largely responsible for the difficulties the Ukraine faces in catching up with Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural areas were practically crippled by outdated machinery parks and the inertia of state-run agriculture modeled after the Soviet pattern.
The rural population sank deep into filth and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is huge.
But our Soviet legacy does not justify everything.
We messed up the reform all by ourselves.
Because often we wanted to import proven concepts from the West—in private property, a free market economy, strict observance of human rights, the creation of a civil society, representative democracy—in a weakened form and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic tendencies in politics, the Supreme Council (the parliament of Ukraine) has over the years adopted civil rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights, which is something akin to a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that had been cut off from European history for centuries was often painful, but has gained momentum, even though we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as open, sentimental, friendly, and family-oriented, but also chaotic and indifferent, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Nevertheless, we are Europeans.
You can see it on the streets and squares of Kyiv.
Today, drivers let pedestrians cross the street, as in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to get out of the way of inconsiderate drivers).
In Kyiv, there is now a lively café scene and friendly public squares where people can pause and enjoy life.
The young people learn English, German, and French, they can handle computers and surf the net in internet cafes.
But these are only the sentimental digressions of someone who loves Kyiv very much.
The sober perspective of the professional politician that I am sees deeper changes.
Over the last ten years, there has been a development from total rejection of reforms through a policy of half-hearted reforms driven by corrupt motives to a gradual introduction of Western practices.
The administrative reform reflects this very vividly.
First, the reform of the state provoked a hostile mood both among bureaucrats and ordinary citizens.
A drastic and thoughtless reduction of civil servants in the public service began.
It was a "by-the-book" reform: the state had to shrink, it was assumed, and then the government would run smoothly.
No one thought about how countries like France or Switzerland somehow manage to thrive with large state apparatuses.
Because the problem is not only a problem of size, but also of organization and efficiency.
The realization that the government does not necessarily become better by simply wielding the red pen led us to the second stage in our reform process.
The state was gradually reformed in a more thoughtful manner.
New departments and positions for state secretaries with clearly defined areas of responsibility were established.
This stabilized the work of the government ministries.
At the beginning, the authority granted to these new areas was somewhat too broad to enable them to carry out their work more effectively.
Now they more or less function normally.
Ukrainians may sometimes get annoyed by these impersonal modern mechanisms, but they are increasingly accepting them as necessary (albeit reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians accept them as well.
Only radicals and populists — of which there are still far too many among us — can afford to take an indifferent attitude toward a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
Ukraine was too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the most important, but still a province.
That has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a by-product of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming feeling of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincialist cannot at all admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
In the measure that we shed our provincial impulse to have to defend ourselves, we open ourselves up to the best that others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was mocked as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, Ukrainians have had to recognize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
Over the course of a decade, we may have contributed to becoming even sicker, but the recently held elections, which have deprived the Communists of their dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly curtailed the power of the "powerful parties" around President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the margins of politics.
The reform parties and the European parties have won.
As European outsiders or at least as a people on the edge of Europe, we want to build a society in which there are no outsiders or marginalized individuals.
As the great and already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all nature's achievements, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, hardship-filled journey toward Europe has helped a weak new nation become strong and survive.
